answers.body_markdown:
You are using the wrong operator here. `^` is [Bitwise XOR][1]. You should be using `**` for [Exponentiation opeartor][2]

Note that, this will return false because `1.001298642 * 10 ** 9` returns  `1001298642.0000001` and not `1001298642` (More on that here: [Is floating point math broken?](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/588004))

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    console.log(1.001298642 * 10 ** 9 == 1001298642)
    console.log(1.001298642 * 10 ** 9)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

---

But, it is interesting that the snippet returns true. `1.001298642*10^9 == 1001298642` enters the `if` block because the expression returns `10` which is a [`truthy`][3] value:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    console.log(1.001298642*10^9 == 1001298642)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

In the [Operator precedence table][4], *Equality operator*(`==`) appears before *Bitwise XOR* (`^`). If you check the the expression in [AST Explorer][5], it is grouped like this:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    (1.001298642*10)^(9 == 1001298642)
    10.01298642 ^ false
    10.01298642 ^ 0 // coerced to zero

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Bitwise_Operators#(Bitwise_XOR)
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Arithmetic_Operators#Exponentiation
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Truthy
  [4]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Operator_Precedence#Table
  [5]: https://astexplorer.net/#/gist/cf6eaa253ff97bd96829c89b11d5987f/774eccf373b71ae2a67a1d84a31a47cdbd9fd388

