You can&#39;t catch compile-time errors, the [`error-boundary`][1] is for run-time errors within the UI.

Refer to [Compile time vs run time errors][2].

Moreover, you have to [use `getDerivedStateFromError`][1] in order to add additional render on fall back UI:

```
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = {
    hasError: false,
    error: { message: &#39;&#39;, stack: &#39;&#39; },
    info: { componentStack: &#39;&#39; }
  };

  static getDerivedStateFromError = error =&gt; {
    return { hasError: true };
  };

  componentDidCatch = (error, info) =&gt; {
    this.setState({ error, info });
  };

  render() {
    const { hasError, error, info } = this.state;
    const { children } = this.props;

    return hasError ? &lt;ErrorComponent/&gt; : children;
  }
}
```

For checking your `ErrorBoundary` throw an error from **a reachable** section in the component tree:

```
throw new Error(&#39;Error thrown&#39;);

// &lt;button onClick={() =&gt; throw new Error(&#39;Error thrown&#39;)}&gt;Throw Error&lt;/button&gt;
```


  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/error-boundaries.html#introducing-error-boundaries
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/846103/runtime-vs-compile-time

