In MVVM, only the View is responsible for changing the way things are displayed. Hence, the background color of your buttons should be **handled in your View** and **not in your ViewModel**. A simple scenario is to use a ```DataTrigger``` in a ```Style``` to change the Background of your button depending on its ```IsSelected``` value:

```xaml
&lt;DataTemplate DataType=&quot;{x:Type engine:ObjA}&quot;&gt;
	&lt;ToggleButton Content=&quot;{Binding Id}&quot;
		IsChecked=&quot;{Binding IsSelected}&quot;
		Height=&quot;{Binding ElementName=ObjItemControl, Path=DataContext.ButtonHeightWidth}&quot;
		Width=&quot;{Binding ElementName=ObjItemControl, Path=DataContext.ButtonHeightWidth}&quot;
		HorizontalAlignment=&quot;Stretch&quot;
        Click= &quot;ToggleButton_Click&quot;
		VerticalAlignment=&quot;Stretch&quot;&gt;
		&lt;ToggleButton.Style&gt;
			&lt;Style TargetType=&quot;ToggleButton&quot;&gt;
				&lt;Setter Property=&quot;Background&quot; Value=&quot;Red&quot;&gt;&lt;/Setter&gt;
				&lt;Style.Triggers&gt;
					&lt;DataTrigger Binding=&quot;{Binding IsSelected}&quot; Value=&quot;True&quot;&gt;
						&lt;Setter Property=&quot;Background&quot; Value=&quot;Blue&quot;&gt;&lt;/Setter&gt;
					&lt;/DataTrigger&gt;
				&lt;/Style.Triggers&gt;
			&lt;/Style&gt;
		&lt;/ToggleButton.Style&gt;
	&lt;/ToggleButton&gt;
&lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
```
You don&#39;t have to change anything in your ViewModel. For more complex behaviors, you should have a look at [Converters](http://www.blackwasp.co.uk/WPFCustomValueConverter.aspx).

You can read [this article from MSDN](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/wpf/controls/styling-and-templating) for more information on Styles.

Then in your code-behind you would have a click event handler from which you can retrieve the view model object:

```cs
private void ToggleButton_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
{
    ToggleButton tb = sender as ToggleButton;
    ObjA objA = tb.DataContext as ObjA;
    //From here you can perform operations on your view model.
}
```

This is a simplified example, in general using the code-behind is not considered good practice and you should have a look at the ```ICommand``` interface for more MVVM-like construction.

